description:
## Why

The parent cannot be implemented safely until the legal field states and the editor value boundary are explicit. Baseline, effective value, sparse intent, origin, external management, writability, and editor capability are related but not interchangeable axes.

## Outcome

Record the smallest public contract and legal-state table that later children implement. Decide:

- which states represent absent, explicit, and locally invalid override intent;
- how effective and baseline values may be present or unavailable;
- how value origin and external management remain orthogonal to sparse intent;
- how capabilities carry staged values and produce SetField values without hidden kind-based authorization;
- how host validation failure is reported while Ratconfig keeps the staged buffer;
- when reset/inherit is available from override presence, baseline knowledge, and source writability;
- which current public fields and enums disappear in the breaking release.

## Constraints

No product schema, callback framework, private config store, compatibility model, or Yazelix-specific type. Prefer data-only enums and existing JsonValue carriers. Keep reset independent of the selected editor capability.

## Verification

Close only when the decision notes contain the chosen Rust-level shape, legal combinations, rejected alternatives, and a migration map from ConfigUiValueState/current_value/default_value/kind/allowed_values/edit_behavior.
